  <header class="bg-blue-800 text-white py-6 text-center">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold">Cardiac Pacemakers: Design, Functionality, and Safety Standards</h1>
    <p class="mt-2 text-lg">A Biomedical Engineering Portfolio</p>
  </header>

  <main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto p-6 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md mt-6">

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-2">Introduction</h2>
      <p>
        Cardiac pacemakers are life-saving devices used to manage abnormal heart rhythms. 
        As implantable technologies become more sophisticated, ensuring their safety and effectiveness 
        through proper design and adherence to regulatory standards is vital.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-2">1. Evolution and Types of Pacemakers</h2>
      <p class="mb-2">
        Over time, pacemakers have evolved from bulky external devices to compact implantable systems. 
        Modern pacemakers are smaller, more efficient, and offer better patient compatibility.
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>Single-Chamber Pacemaker:</strong> Stimulates either the right atrium or right ventricle. Often used for patients with atrial fibrillation or bradycardia.</li>
        <li><strong>Dual-Chamber Pacemaker:</strong> Stimulates both the right atrium and ventricle, maintaining synchrony in heartbeats and better mimicking natural rhythm.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-2">2. Electrical Safety in Pacemaker Use</h2>
      <p>
        Pacemakers must adhere to strict electrical safety standards to prevent hazards such as:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4 space-y-2">
        <li>Electromagnetic interference from external devices (e.g., MRI, mobile phones)</li>
        <li>Overheating or battery leakage</li>
        <li>Safe energy delivery to cardiac tissue without causing burns or arrhythmias</li>
        <li>Fail-safe mechanisms for sudden power loss</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-2">3. Regulatory and Safety Standards</h2>
      <p>
        Regulatory bodies ensure devices meet international safety requirements:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>FDA (U.S.):</strong> Oversees premarket approval, labeling, and post-market surveillance</li>
        <li><strong>ISO 14708-2:</strong> Specifies testing requirements for active implantable medical devices like pacemakers</li>
        <li><strong>IEC 60601-1:</strong> General requirements for basic safety and essential performance</li>
        <li><strong>CE Marking (Europe):</strong> Indicates conformity with EU health and safety directives</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-2">4. Safety Testing and Validation</h2>
      <p>Safety and functionality are validated through rigorous testing:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4 space-y-2">
        <li>Electrical stimulation threshold testing</li>
        <li>Battery longevity and fail-safe testing</li>
        <li>Biocompatibility and corrosion resistance</li>
        <li>Simulated physiological condition testing</li>
        <li>Long-term in vivo studies and clinical trials</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-2">Block Diagram</h2>
